inn1.comm: wide of off stump, the swing takes it away towards the slips, but a handy amount of movement nonetheless
a bit wider but not called as such. Good carry once again through to McCullum
width again, and Joyce lays bat on ball for the first time in the match. Doesn't time his steer through the covers though
yorker, and a good one too. Joyce jabs his bat down just in time as his toes retreat to square-leg
full and straight, and defended watchfully back up the pitch
excellent first over, right on the money to finish. Joyce defends and the ball bobbles a couple of yards from the bat
oops, that slipped. Passed the popping crease on the full, and tidied up by the keeper

GOT HIM! And what a ball to do it with! Full and inswinging, Vaughan was beaten for pace as he jabbed down late on the crease. The ball zipped beneath his bat and onto middle stump! Jubilation for the Kiwis, and England's captain lasts just one delivery on comeback!
fizzing inswing from Bond, and that clips the thigh-pad before flying high through to the keeper! A bit of excitement from the fielders, but Bond is pumped up
overcooked it again
veers onto the pads, and turned square
misdirected again, but good hostile pace - only timed at 86mph (138kph) but it's looking sharper than that. Turned into the leg-side and Bell is off the mark
short, and that zips past the edge, Joyce does well to get his bat out of the way
another attempted yorker, but outswinging to the left-hander, and defended easily enough outside off stump. Excellent over!
full-length, and Bell comes down the pitch to meet it, pushed away into the covers
angling across the right-hander, and prodded into the covers again
shot! A full toss, but excellently clubbed away through the covers. England's first boundary and a good one too
misdirected this time, and turned into the leg-side to rotate the strike
better line to the left-hander. Joyce is drawn forward and defends off the front foot
full and floated onto a length. Defended again
a wafty, woolly swish that time. Maybe a hint of late swing, but well beaten as he came down the track to loft that into the leg-side. Still not off the mark, and maybe the pressure is telling a bit
forward and nudged into the covers. A loud "NOO!" as Bell looks for the run
inswinger tucks Bell up, but good running to steal a single as the ball deflects down to third man
too short and Joyce is into position early for the pull. Not quite timed though and they pick up a couple through square leg
better line and length. Watchfully defended back up the pitch
pitches middle-and-leg, angled across the left-hander and towards the slips. Defended again
slightly shorter, but the same result. Defended off the back foot into the covers. Good over again
good busy running between the wickets. Dabbed into the leg-side and a quick scamper for a single. Well played
angled onto the pads, turned to midwicket
fuller and speared into the stumps from wide of the crease. Joyce plays with deft hands to flick it down to fine leg
sweet clip through midwicket for four! Excellent timing, just a fraction off-line, but Bell was into position well with quick feet and solid contact
shorter, and a dabbed cut down to third man. Good controlled follow-up
that's a nice shot. Nothing more than a floaty half-volley from Franklin, but it still needed to be put away. And Joyce obliged, just beating two chasing fielders at extra cover
drawn forward in defence. That's the end of a useful over for England
brisk again, and fizzes through to the keeper. 86.6mph, which is roughly 139kph
shorter, and zips back off the seam as Bell shoulders arms
a bit too much width that time. Easily left alone by Bell
fuller, and dug out again with a straight and defensive bat
probing that corridor of uncertainty, as they say. A bit too wide to induce a stroke though
that was a bit wide again, but Bell had a nibble this time. Got away with it, but that's a useful maiden over for New Zealand.
indifferent start, slightly leg-sided, and clipped to midwicket
that's good running. Nudged into the leg-side and they set off at once. Annoying for the bowler
wide of off stump, but not too wide for the umpire's liking. Left well alone by Bell
nice shot for no runs. Drawn forward into a full-blooded cover-drive, but can't beat the field
similar shot, similar result. A bit full and wide, steered to cover again. Two let-offs for New Zealand
more forceful strokeplay, but a half-stop in the covers cuts off another probable boundary. "A bit of a let-off," says Nasser Hussain, and he's got a point
more pacy inswing from Bond, and dug out again
outside off stump, Bell shoulders arms
good rhythm so far from Bond. That one is in the channel once again, and Bell leaves alone once again
drawn into the stroke this time, but again picks out the fielder with an attempted dab to third man. A touch frustrating, but he's a phlegmatic chap
another attractive stroke, but once again he's picked out that ring of fielders in the covers

GONE! And that's pure frustration that's done for Bell! With a bit of luck and placement he could have had four boundaries in the last two overs. Instead he's been becalmed by some good fielding, and now he's chased a full delivery outside off stump, and edged a regulation chance to second slip!
short, and pulled without much power to midwicket
trouble for Strauss, but he's home! Joyce clipped to leg, thought about a single but belatedly changed his mind
defended again. Good tight bowling
he's found a good line and length now. Acting as an excellent foil to the pacy Bond at the other end
and as I say that, he drops short and wide, and Joyce clobbers him past point for a welcome boundary. Well played
more attacking intent from Joyce, but his attempted pull dribbles out to midwicket
short, fizzes past Strauss's chest as he sways out of line
short again but wider. Strauss keeps his bat inside the line
good strike. This time the timing and placement is just right, as the ball zips past a flailing short midwicket
better line and length
left alone outside off stump again
full and speared in towards off stump. Defended with a straight bat
short again, and Gillespie gets away with it once again. Pulled firmly, but straight to midwicket. England's intent hasn't been lacking so far, but their placement definitely has
fuller, and straighter. Defended into the covers
big swish of the bat, but mid-off tidies up with minimal fuss
wider of the crease, and clipped through fine leg. A half-stop by Bond at leg-gully stops the boundary, but England get three nonetheless
fuller length from over the wicket, and defended
half an appeal as the ball pitches outside leg. Strauss is squared up as the ball deflects to gully
floated onto a full length, good stop by Vettori at mid-on stops another boundary. New Zealand have been keen in the field today
no cutting that one off. Into position early, and eased through long-on by Joyce. Good shot
good riposte, outside off stump and a flinched defensive shot as the ball fizzed by
in the good channel again. Joyce makes to defend but is beaten again
clipped off the hip, another single to the cause
too full again from Franklin and that's worked easily into the leg-side for another single. And that's over
defended again. Good waspish length
no width on offer there. Pushed into the covers
drifting onto the pads, but Strauss can't make clean contact with his attempted clip. He's not in the best of form
oversteps, and Strauss steers that down to third man to escape the strike
fuller length but wider, left alone
the first genuinely attacking stroke of the day, and it pays handsome dividends for Joyce - down the track, smacked over the top for an excellent boundary
back on a good length to complete the over
on off stump, blocked into the off side
angled through the vacant third slip area, deliberate shot but he had to squeeze that down there as it was a tad closer to him that he wanted

one step down the track, a shimmy to leg to give himself room, an ugly swish, a thin nick and a straightforward catch. England are now in deep trouble. Can we hear the sound of Duncan Fletcher on the phone to British Airways confirming the flights home tomorrow ...
off the mark confidently, working the ball between mid-on and  midwicket
straight and full, driven back to the bowler but not timed and it barely has the legs to make it to Franklin in his follow-through
outside off stump and left alone. 85mph (137kph) for all you speed men ...
punched into the off side, again not timed
Collingwood back and across to defend
outside off stump, Collingwood not interested in a nibble. 89mph (143kph)
even wider and this time Collingwood smacks it to the left of point, third man has to scurry round quite some way to field
full on off stump, driven to mid-on where Vettori takes it on the bounce and underarms down the stumps at the non-striker's end. Not sure why, but it probably made him feel better
wide and slightly short, no shot. Collingwood has to rebuild and so don't expect any risks for a while yet
driven to short extra cover where it is athletically stopped
Strauss drives with an open face past the despairing dive of cover point
short, Strauss pulls from off stump, not really timed and Vettori shuffles round from deep midwicket to field

clipped off his toes, Vettori again in quickly and a quick pick-up and throw causes chaos and Collingwood has to dive back to make his ground. Had the throw been accurate then he would have been a couple of yards short
beaten defending on the back foot, too high for any appeal to be taken seriously
driven to mid-off
Strauss pushed slightly tentatively to extra cover
well-timed cut but very well stopped in the gully
driven through extra cover, he placed that into the gap sweetly, Vincent chased it down and pulled the ball up a yard inside the rope with a forward lunge ... but they ran four anyway
banged in, Strauss onto that in a flash and he launches it into the crowd ... er, the empty seats ... over midwicket
leg side, flicked off his hips fine, too much so for long leg to be able to get round to stop
Strauss back, pushes it into the leg side but mid-on rushes in and no run
Collingwood solid, into line and blocks
one step forward and a checked drive to mid-on
overpitched on leg stump, Collingwood effortlessly flicks it over the infield and all the way to the midwicket rope
dropped into space created by the fielding change and an ambled single
short and Strauss doesn't get hold of a pull and it bobbles out to Vettori at deepish midwicket
beaten but it raps him on the pads and trickles to slip. Far too high to warrant an appeal
loosener tucked away for an easy single
Collingwood blocks into the off side, a shout of "no" from both ends as the cover fielders sprint in
same line and length - slightly short on off stump - and Collingwood can do no more than block into the off
too much width and Collingwood steers it down to third man, wide enough of Bond to enable them to come back for an easy second
similar shot, this time right at Bond and no chance of a second
whipped into the leg side. Strauss is actually looking confident for almost the first time in the series
loud shout as Strauss is beaten aiming to swat it across the line, it looked a good appeal but nothing doing
Collingwood bangs it into the ground as he defends
too full and Collingwood flicks that to deep midwicket. He plays that shot well, and that's why Fleming has had to reinforce that area
Franklin overcorrects, Collingwood throws everything at a wide one and the ball races to the backward point rope
tip and run with no alarms
Strauss tries to cut through gully but hits it straight at the man there
patted into the off side, a crisp and quick shout of "no"
dropped full, driven hard back at Oram who gets a hand on it - it was actually a catch low to his right - and deflects the ball into the stumps, but Strauss was just back
placed into the off side for a single
again steered to his favourite gully area but that is well defended
pushed towards midwicket, Strauss sets off but is quickly sent back by Collingwood's shout
pushed up to mid-on
turned to the right of midwicket but well fielded
hit straighter to deepish mid-on. One there every time
driven with ease to mid-on who is giving the one
Collingwood chips over the infield but gets far too much on it and it goes for a two-bounce four over wide long-on. The man down there got close but not close enough
flicked behind fine on the leg side
good running, turned no more than 25 yards towards square leg but into space
Collingwood looks to cut but it's too close to his body and so he can't get any power on it and point fields easily
turned towards backward square leg, bisecting deep midwicket and long leg and so another two
Collingwood into line and blocks as Oram follows through to prevent any quick run
into line, solid defensive shot with the full face of the bat
back and a punch into the covers not timed. 73mph (118kph)  which is only 13mph faster than Panesar!
pushed up to mid-on
too wide and cut to the cover boundary where the man has been posted for just that shot
no more than a defensive prod, but placed and a good, quick call means an easy one
outside off, Strauss leaves and McCullum can only parry as the ball kicks off a length
flipped to midwicket
driven straightishly on the leg and a good dive by the man in saving the one does just that
driven to deep mid-on for the single
on a good line and length again, pushed into the off side
tight again, defended into the covers with a loud "NOO!"
a fraction shorter and a bit of width, steered down to third man with a cross-batted deflection
the same but this time a left-handed version from Strauss. Good rotation of the strike
slightly short, and a shovelled drive is cut off in Oram's followthrough. That's a long way for a tall man to stoop
bouncer! A quick glance to the square-leg umpire confirms that that wasn't too short to be legitimate, and that's the end of a tidy over
short, and that's a wafty cut from Strauss. Lucky to get away with it as McCullum takes
clipped into the leg-side, and an untidy misfield allows them back for two. Vettori is justifiably miffed, although that did bobble unkindly for Vincent
clipped into the leg-side again. Tip-and-run stuff
nicely weighted stroke from Collingwood. Not enough power to reach a deep cover quickly, so two easy runs
tighter and better from Vettori. Defended
nurdled once more, picked up at midwicket to complete a nicely milked over for England. Vettori is a little miffed still
a fraction short, whipped into the leg-side but without any great power
short and that's well clobbered through midwicket, but a sliding stop on the boundary's edge cuts off a couple. Good fielding
width on the off-side this time, and Strauss thumps that square - in the air for a while, but clear of a diving point. A little ragged from New Zealand at the moment
better areas. Outside off, rising off a good length. Defended into the gully
tip-and-run stuff. England working the singles nicely now
dabbed down to third man. Excellent strike rotation
decent start, stump-to-stump stuff, turned into the leg side
fuller, a hint of inswing, driven into the leg-side for another sharp single
that was tight enough, pushed into the covers
wider, and walloped but it's a thick edge at a catchable height through gully. No-one there though, safe enough
clipped down to fine leg
one more to the total, turned into the leg-side and a scamper
tip-and-run, and nearly a run-out! Strauss played a flat slap through midwicket, Vincent pounced, picked up and threw on his knees. A direct hit would have been out!
watchful this time. Defended
two steps down the track and a firm clip through square leg. New Zealand aren't too happy at the moment
drawn onto the front foot, and defended into the leg-side. Another jogged single. Gaps everywhere
a touch wider, and nudged down to third man for Strauss's half-century! Well played, and dare one suggest it, not before time
another good nurdle finds the gap and rotates the strike. England press onwards and upwards
tucked off the pads and that's another easy run through midwicket
tighter line
fuller and wider, Strauss throws the kitchen sink at this one, but can't time it and cover tidies up
clipped square again. Too full from Styris
driven back down the ground but only as far as mid-off
better ball to finish, a more challenging length rising at the bat. Defended into the gully
a touch short, Collingwood rocks back to cut but no great timing. Still finds the gap though
good ball, hint of turn back into the left-hander. Whipped through midwicket
flattish delivery outside off. Collingwood misses out
more flighted this time. Solid defence back down the track
turned to short cover, still no width to play with
tidy stuff from Vettori. This end seems to suit him better
attempted cut, but that's too close to Strauss's body, and so there's no power
flicked behind square, Oram tidies up on the fine-leg boundary. Singles are the order of England's innings so far
a bottom-handed drive, but again, no great power. Styris fields in his followthrough
flicked through wide midwicket. Good placement from these two batsmen, which is compensating for the lack of power
tighter line
a bit of a wild carve but Strauss is too late and that's another over done and dusted
driven through point, another single. They all count
good use of the feet and a punchy drive down the ground to long-off
well steered into the leg-side. Good running from this pair once again, and that's another fifty for England. Collingwood removes his helmet, and waves his bat at the dressing-room, and well he might
good measured lofted drive over cover. Didn't try to leather it, but placed it well
one more to the total, could have been hit a bit squarer perhaps
flicked through midwicket to complete another useful nurdle-tastic over for England

Strauss can't capitalise! That's a horrid smear across the line - he was targeting the vacant midwicket region, but missed a typical wicket-to-wicket delivery from Styris and lost the top of his middle stump. Another fifty-and-out for Strauss!
watchfully forward to start his innings off. Flintoff's defensive strokes always seem so exaggerated, as if he's willing himself not to have a slog
clipped square this time, and he's off the mark
another easy single as Collingwood defends into the leg-side
fuller length and a touch of inswing. Flintoff drives as McCullum enthuses "Ooh nice Scotty mate!"
strays onto the legs again, and another whipped single to finish
pushed into the off side
drawn onto the front foot, driven to long on
a bit chancy from Flintoff. Pushes forward tentatively and a big deflection out to point. Appeal for lbw but slipping down leg
more confidently forward, and driven to long-on this time
shot! Short, and clobbered through midwicket. Loose delivery
another single to the total. Good nurdling again
cut to point off the front foot
good length delivery - brisk as well - and left alone
tight and attacking. Turned to midwicket off a good length
short and quick. Collingwood is up on his toes and cutting to point
short again but straighter, defended with a solid bat
steered down to third man to deprive Bond of his maiden. Excellent incisive over though
the bottom hand comes into play again, as Collingwood flicks down to long-on
short and straying down leg. Flintoff has a great mow, but can't quite time it. James Franklin fields at square leg
clipped to short midwicket, but no way through there
fuller length and Collingwood is forward onto the drive. Ross Taylor fields in the covers
shorter and tipped round the corner. Collingwood hurtles through for a mighty quick first run, and is safely back for a second as the ball comes in from fine leg. Good running
low full toss, but Collingwood can't get it away. Quite an effective delivery in one-day cricket, to be honest
full length, pushed back to the bowler
short and shovelled round the corner! Excellent shot, picks the gap well and another handy boundary to the cause
played into the deep, Franklin comes in from the boundary to field
short, and thumped off the front foot with a swivel for good effect! Great strike from Flintoff as the ball whistles in front of square
leg-sided this time, and clipped round the corner for one more
short and rising over off stump. Collingwood is back in defence, hopping as he does so
full length, speared into the legs and driven into the off-side
width and Flintoff's eyes light up! But he's lucky not to drag that ball on from outside off stump. Instead it bounces off his pads and comes to a rest in the crease
forward again, more circumspect this time
dropped! And that's an absolute clanger from Ross Taylor at deep midwicket! A smear into the deep, Taylor got into position but the ball burst straight through his fingers and away to the boundary!
driven into the off-side. Watchful from Flintoff, and finds the gap well
jeers from the crowd as Taylor fields one-handed at midwicket. It's a bit late for showboating
full length, Collingwood comes forward and defends into the covers
short and Collingwood is into position for the pull, only to bale out at the last minute. I think it was a slower ball bouncer, which is an interesting variation
forward and dabbed into the covers to give Flintoff the strike

Relief for Ross Taylor as Flintoff thumps a simple chance straight down Franklin's throat at long-on! It was in the slot for the shot, but that was precisely the problem, as the man was lying in wait. A sucker-punch for England, and now the burden falls squarely on Collingwood's shoulders
Ouch! Short and hostile, and Collingwood is thumped painfully on the fingers. The ball flies safe though
short again but off target, and another extra to the total
an enthusiastic appeal for lbw, but a tad optimistic
genuine edge off an indifferent swish, through second slip and past Fleming who was around third
similar area but Dalrymple more circumspect and he lets it pass
straight full toss, cracked hard to mid-off
wide of off stump and Dalrymple again watches it pass. 84mph (135kph)
full outside off stump, driven with a hint of an edge to the left of point
Collingwood back and punches to mid-on, a moment of hesitation from Dalrymple before he sets off
crisp drive right at short extra cover
worked to the leg side for an ambled one
dead bat into the covers, fielders converge and no chance of a run
half volley driven all along the ground to deepish mid-on
too short and drifting to leg, turned behind square and he again places it so well that they run the second
driven slightly uppishly to deep mid-on
shapes to play a nothing swat into the off side, but he hammers it down into the pitch instead and it goes nowhere
placed through the gap in the covers
short, pulled and inches short of Ross Taylor who did really well to even go for the catch as it needed him to run in and dive forward about 15 yards inside the rope
pushed into the off, a wild throw and a superb leaping take from McCullum to prevent overthrows
strangled by the off-side field
just short of a length and Dalrymple can't force it away
punch-drive to long-on and quick running as they come back for a second they shouldn't have been allowed
Colllingwood opens the face and runs it behind square on the off
Dalrymple opens the face even more, it goes finer but still only the one
placed into the gap on the leg side
premeditated sweep which he doesn't really get hold of and it bobbles behind square on the leg
straight and defended but never a single
worked past midwicket, they call for two but that was mindgames as it was never on without a misfield
squeezed through gully, another single. New Zealand won't mind them getting a run a ball
pushed to mid-off, a scampered single
flat-batted between cover and extra cover, swept up in the deep
Collingwood waits and whips it off his hips to backward square leg, back for the second as the Ross Taylor had a few yards to make and he didn't pick that up cleanly
smacked with venom over the bowler and second bounce past the full-length dive of the man at long-off
Collingwood accepts the invitation and runs one to the midwicket region
paddled to square leg, between two fielders on the rope and so they get the second with ease
wide half volley, super stop diving to his left at point by Fleming saves four
a swish and a top edge right over McCullum's head, no way to defend that
made room, a bullet-straight drive along the ground and the men in the deep never had a chance
driven to the sweeper, again good running puts pressure on the fielder and they should not have got two there
driven to deep cover again, tumbling stop, an easy two
straight drive but not hit as hard and only the one
again hit down the ground, long-on in quickly
full toss, Dalrymple stepping to leg hits it high on the bat and it drops short of long-off
full toss down the leg side and inexplicably no wide called ... it didn't hit anything and McCullum gives a wry smile like a boy who has got away with pinching a sweet
smacked to long-on
pushed from outside off stump to long-on, a well run second as well
lovely stroke, whipped from middle stump behind square on the leg
Collingwood steps to leg and flat bats the ball over the top of the cover ring
slower ball which Dalrymple picked, waited for, and ran down fine to third man

leg-side yorker, Collingwood, stepping to the off, is bowled round his legs. He departs scowling at Dalrymple who dropped his bat at the non-striker's end as Bond was in his delivery stride ...  and as the ball was delivered he was scrambling around in the dirt trying to pick it up!
straight slower ball which Nixon blocks
pushed down the ground
carbon-copy dismissal ... Nixon shuffles to the off to try to flick the ball to the on side and a full delivery clips his leg stump
missed an attempted drive on the front foot
worked gently into the leg side
full toss, hammered back with interest, Gillespie sticks out his right boot and takes the pace off it as well as deflecting it to a fielder
smeared through extra cover to the man on the rope
wild swing, a thick edge over where the slips would have been and four all the way. Bond scowls but it was too short and too wide
dropped slower ball clipped to Fulton at midwicket ... he moved about five yards but spilt the ball having done the hard work
smacked to wide long-off, always two
slower ball again, Dalrymple opens the face and runs it to third man
fast leg-side full toss (89.9mph - 144kph) which is just helped on tis way behind square for four
big hit high into space at to deep midwicket, they ran two but a wild throw gives another two more  overthrow. That sums up some mediocre fielding from New Zealand and Bond is seething

inn2.comm: wide of off stump, and that's an extravagent amount of swing taking it wider still
too much movement again, but there's plenty doing out there
a play-and-a-miss - wide again, but this time not called as such
this one is on the other hand. A few problems for Plunkett here
yikes. That's horrific. Speared down the leg side, wide and wider. Nixon can't get close to it!
ironic cheers as he gets one on target. But that was a good ball. Full length, hint of swing, defensively played
much better, good shape and carry as Fleming shoulders arms
beaten outside off stump, that's Fleming's lack of form doing the work there. No real need to play at it but he was tempted all the same
good areas. Fleming is forward with soft hands
err ... another wide. Down the leg-side this time
and there's the end of the over. A tortuous start but a straighter delivery to finish things off. Deflects off the knee-roll into the leg-side
a low full-toss and sloppy work from Dalrymple at short cover, who allows the ball to bobble away for a single
outside off stump, carved down to third man. A nervy start from England
sharp and back of a length, nudged down to third man
and now a regulation half-volley, and Fleming leans into that with glee. Picks the gap in the covers, and New Zealand are off to a flier
pushed onto the back foot, and defended
shorter, and pulled away over midwicket for another three. A hint of a top-edge, but it beat the infield easily enough
much better line and length, fizzes past off stump
straighter and curving back into the pads. Fleming jabs his bat down in defence
straying down leg once again, tickled fine and Nixon sheds a glove to field
rubbish. Plunkett loses his action at the last minute - his wrist position was spearing that one down leg from the moment it left the hand
better. On the line of off stump and defended into the gully
good grief. Scott Boswell eat your heart out. That started wide of off stump and was swinging wider
straighter and possibly faster as well. Plunkett was so surprised he forgot to appeal for lbw!
good finish, swinging back into off stump and pushed up to mid-off
edged straight through the slip cordon! Excellent length from Mahmood and Vincent was flailing outside off. Flintoff, positioned wide at second slip, couldn't get across
turned into the leg-side to escape the strike
circumspect defence. No need to rush with this many freebies on offer
a wide half-volley and Fleming gives it the big wind-up ... but it goes nowhere
fuller, and driven firmly, but straight at Dalrymple at short cover
England shipped more extras in Plunkett's first over than New Zealand managed in the whole of their innings
fuller and straighter, which is a good combination. Steered into the covers.
that's not good enough. Wide, short, clobbered in front of point off the back foot. New Zealand are at the buffet at the moment
play and a miss off the back foot
much better ball. Tighter, angled across the left-hander. Fleming wafts outside off and nearly gets the edge
turned into the leg-side
attempted yorker, not a bad one, but swinging too far down leg. Clipped to square leg
good line and length from Mahmood. Well, better, at any rate. Tighter and a touch shorter, so climbing at the bat
more freebies for New Zealand! Speared onto the pads, and Fleming clips fine for another boundary!
leg-sided again. Ill-disciplined stuff, and another clipped single
tighter line and length, Vincent comes forward and defends
slower ball, down to 70mph (112kph). At least, England will hope it was a slower ball!
onto the front foot again, picks the gap on the off side for one more
wonderful fielding from Panesar! A full-length dive at backward square cuts off a certain boundary. Who says this man can't field?
drawn onto the front foot, pushed to extra cover
down the leg-side again, but an appeal saves Plunkett from another wide. Might there even have been a bit of an edge on that shot?
.... and another one. Down the leg-side this time. It's a bit village
no confidence in that delivery, and Fleming latched onto it in an instant, clobbering him high over the covers! They are flying!
floaty floaty ... thwack! Fleming leans into another indifferent delivery, and creams it to the long-on boundary!
defended to finish another x-rated over for England. Suddenly New Zealand need 218 from 43 overs. A doddle?
87.3mph first-up (140kph) and in the channel outside off stump
good bowling, bouncing high over off stump from a good length
edged! And a genuine edge as well. Drawn forward and properly beaten. Only one slip and a gully, and that bisected them both!
a touch wider, and Vincent - sensibly - leaves well alone
clobbered off a good length, through midwicket. That was disdainful, but it wasn't quite timed, and Mahmood sweeps up on the boundary's edge
outside off, Fleming withdraws the bat
a bit dicey there from Vincent! A thump off the back foot into the covers, and he decided to take on Paul Collingwood's arm. Fortunately for him, the throw was wayward, because he was well out
oops, a chinese cut deflects down to fine leg. Fleming looks around in alarm but the ball misses the off stump by enough
short and straighter. Vincent shoulders arms
attempted yorker, and not a bad one either. Speared in at pace, and chiselled up to mid-off
flicked square for another single. England need to change the tempo somehow here. Maybe an early burst for Panesar?
better line and length, and a better over all round. That one is defended into the covers
good tight line outside off stump, left well alone
thrown out wider, might have been called as such but Fleming, down on one knee, went after it and mistimed it back to the bowler
fizzed through again. Nixon takes on the second bounce
good pace and carry - this one is taken at chest height by Nixon, just outside off stump
tidy again. Fleming bides his time after his helter-skelter start
and would you believe it? A maiden for England! This one is straighter but Fleming can't time his clip into the leg-side. Flintoff has restored a modicum of over
hint of swing but no great pace. Right up in Vincent's slot who slaps this over mid-off. It goes high but doesn't have much distance on it, and plugs into the turf ten yards inside the rope
lovely straight drive, too straight in fact, and the stumps do the fielding for England. A let-off
a sizeable appeal for lbw, but this one pitches outside leg, so an easy enough decision for umpire Harper
clipped into the leg-side to bring Vincent back onto strike
another confident stride and strike, but Flintoff is in the deep to sweep up
a one-handed skewed drive, picked up on the slide by deep point. Seven off the over
good length to start, pushed into the covers
down on one knee, and swept fine. Thought about a second, but wisely turned it down
drawn forward again, and a good quick single into the covers
well bowled, beaten in flight and mistimed an attempted drive
asking the question, but struck Vincent outside the line
reverse sweep, and wonderfully executed. The slip had just been taken out, so he slotted the ball straight through the hands of the phantom fielder!
soft hands, dropped into the off side and a good understanding as they scamper a single
slow ball, driven rather gently to cover point
top-edged cut, quite safe, Plunkett scurries round and fields at fine leg
dropped Fleming looks to run the ball fine, gets an outside edge ... Nixon, who had no real chance, fails to hold the ball and it cannons off his gloves for one
pushed into space, easy single
Fleming beaten outside off stump, Nixon whips the bails off
Vincent tries to hit against the spin, gets a massive top edge and Flintoff, a few feet inside the 30-yard circle at mid-on, waits and waits and then holds the catch with nonchalant ease
pushed through, Fleming forward to block
again pushed through and once more Fleming forward to block
he looks to work that round on the leg but doesn't get it fine enough to find the space
Fleming onto the front foot to defend
this time he angles the bat, still defensively, looking for a gap on the off without any result
right into the groove from the off ... some of his colleagues could learn from that
again no leeway given to Fulton and he has to be happy with another defensive block
good line and just fractionally short of a length, Fulton drops it into the leg side
Fulton forced on to the back foot to defend
super stuff ... Fulton is being given nothing to play with, and he shimmies down the track after another block but more in frustration than expectation
join the dots ... Fulton pushes to short extra cover. A really classy one-day maiden
full, driven hard back at Panesar and then throw back even harder by Flintoff. Panesar scowls
clipped to leg, good diving stop by mid-on
again he finds the man at mid-on
defended into the off side
that did the trick!  Angled into space on the off side and the stranglehold is eased a little
gently pushed past the close fielder
into the off side, a very low-key resumption
Fleming decides fairly late to leave one outside off stump
banged in, Fleming tries to pull, misses and Flintoff lets rip an appeal ...Nixon doesn't back his bowler and the umpire agrees with the keeper
slightly uppish and unconvincing swish to third man
Fulton forced back and Flintoff moves easily to his right to field. Fulton a bit bogged down here ...
Fulton again back to block. Flintoff has his length sorted and Fulton seems unable to work out yet how to tackle it
a smidgen too wide and that allows Fleming to punch it through the gap between cover and extra cover
Fulton forward. "Oh, that's good," chirps Nixon
Fulton finally off the mark with a thick outside edge off a defensive push
driven to one of three men 10-15 yards in on the off side
straight drive to mid-on for a single
well worked into space. Much better, the scoreboard is again moving
dug in and Fleming undone by the pace (88mph) and he ends up top edging fine on the leg and Nixon chases the ball down. Not a catch but a definite moral victory to the bowler
short of a length and Fulton back to defend
All the time ... Flintoff to Fulton and no run. Same line and length and Fulton can do no more than block it
this time Flintoff gives him some width and like a starving man offered a sandwich, Fulton pounces and smashes it over wide mid-on for a one bounce four.
normal service resumed as Fulton forced back to block. If it wasn't for replays that last ball and shot might have come from a different match
snorter of a bouncer, just outside off stump, and Fulton jags his head back. Flintoff scowls ...he didn't like being belted
good start, on off stump and played into the covers
bad ball, no setting a field for that, down the leg side and helped on its way. Vaughan keeps his emotions in check ...
inside edge into the leg side, the return throw goes over Nixon's head by some way ... sloppy
good line, good length, good grief
Fulton pushes straight and takes a step down the pitch as if to run but it is never on
straighter and hit into the pitch, it bounces over Plunkett and mid-off round to field but this time there is the single
Fulton into line to defend. Aside from that one glorious four, Flintoff has him tied down ...
speared in at leg stump, much fuller than most balls so far, Fulton shapes to flick it away but it is through him before he completes the shot and it smacks him on the pads
more width, a loose and airy swish and miss from Fulton ... Flintoff looks to the heavens
very unusual waywardness outside off stump
Flintoff feeds Fulton where he likes it, on his legs, and he clips it into space on the leg side
ripper, another indecisive prod which beats Fulton's outside edge
driven to mid-off
slightly back of a length, nudged into space
good ball, straight and pretty swift, defended uncomfortably
better rhythm now. Fleming defends in front of off stump
slightly shorter and banged into the thigh-pad. The Kiwi contingent in the crowd rise to acclaim their captain's half-century ... but not yet, they'll have to wait
bouncer! And a good one too, short and fizzing past the chest

well, well ... Plunkett has his man, and that is due reward for a fine over. Fulton went for the pull, was through the shot too early, and a steepling top-edge plopped comfortably into the hands of Ian Bell in the covers
well, that's a handy start - a bit of a half-volley from Plunkett, but Taylor leans into it and strokes it through the covers for a first-ball four
pushed into the covers. Better line
shorter but on off stump. Deflected into space behind point and there's another single
good ball, angled across the left-hander, who couldn't resist a little nibble
pushed into the off-side, to the left of point, and that's Fleming's 46th ODI fifty. Well done skipper, it's been a struggle for form of late, but class will always come through. Well, usually
defended off the front foot. End of a decent over
that's short and ill-directed, and Fleming just helps that round the corner and over the head of fine leg for another boundary!
better - in that channel outside off stump, and left alone. It's been a traumatic day for Plunkett so far, but still time to redeem himself
carbon copy. Fleming shoulders arms. Six of those an over would not go amiss
fuller, more or less a half-volley, but slapped straight to short cover
drawn forward and a defensive push takes the inside edge and flies away for a single into the leg-side
shorter and sharper, Taylor is pushed back onto his stumps and defends
nice bowling - a slower ball, well disguised, and through to the keeper on the third bounce
good areas, Saj, good areas. Defended into the covers
drilled off the front foot, but only as far as mid-off. That was another slower ball. A sign, perhaps, of his increased confidence
top-edged ... but safe! That was chancy. Short and flew high down to fine leg, but Plunkett couldn't quite get there in time
quicker, and Taylor ducks. Good bowling
slower again, down to 70mph (112kph) that delivery, and turned into the leg-side. Tidy stuff from Mahmood
twirled onto a good length and nudged away
tidy stuff, Fleming is drawn out of his crease to defend
dragged out of his crease again, and pushed into the covers
good areas, Monty. No freebies for Fleming
defended off the front foot, tidy once again
looped up outside off stump and driven down to long-on to complete an excellent over
shuffled across and plays out to cover, but a bad throw results in an extra run, and then there's a misfield as well to complete an untidy passage of play
clubbed back over the bowler's head! Sweet strike!
A swish and a miss from Fleming - something of an appeal as the ball fizzes by. Seemed to strike his hip?
pushed into the covers. This is much more disciplined from England
down the leg-side again, and worked off the hip to fine leg.
short and sharp. Fleming is pushed back onto his stumps as he defends
flicked out to midwicket
defended back to the bowler
turned to silly mid-off. Tight, loopy stuff
lovely lofted strike, flies high down towards long-on! New Zealand's skipper is coming to the party
even better shot - blazed through the covers with a firm stride and a full swing! Lovely batting
flatter and faster, and defended
clipped behind square on the leg-side
banged in halfway down the pitch, passes over Fleming's shoulder as he ducks, but no wide signalled
that's a bit impetuous from Fleming. Short again and he went for a big mow across the line. Lucky not to graze an edge through to the keeper
Michael Vaughan's dodgy knee, (or is it hamstring these days?) is put to the test as he sets off in pursuit of a clip through midwicket. Not the most mobile, it must be said
short and a bit rubbish. Down the leg-side, reaches the keeper on the second bounce
better line, driven to mid-off
drawn forward again, and picks the gap in the covers
good variation of pace. Pushed into the covers
slightly shorter but a hint of turn, and defended watchfully
forward again, and turned into the leg-side
nice flight and turn, deceived Fleming but the appeal for lbw was always optimistic
glanced behind square
clever batting, dinked behind square on the leg-side, and Collingwood is in a bit of trouble as he fields well on the boundary
a stutter and a stop - confusion between the batsmen, but they recover their poise before the throw comes in from midwicket
onto the back foot, and pushed straight back down the pitch
shorter, but not too short. Cut to point
forward again, and nurdled into the leg-side
fuller, with a hint of swing. Defensively played
wider, and Taylor throws the kitchen sink at it, but point leaps to cut off any chance of a run. Tidy over
good start, nice flight and loop onto a good length outside off
driven with a flourish down to long-off, but no great power
shorter, but wicket-to-wicket. Taylor clips firmly in front of square, and runs two very well
another clip into space on the leg-side, but Panesar swoops to limit them to a single. Good fielding
chipped to midwicket - it was in the air for a little while as well. Good stuff from Dalrymple
slightly down the leg-side, but Fleming can't time his sweep. Decent first over
swatted into the leg-side, and that was nearly the breakthrough! Strauss at short midwicket leapt but couldn't quite reach the ball as it lobbed past his left hand
that was a touch impetuous too  - driven in the air over extra cover. Frustration for England, but New Zealand march on
more good runs, a bit of width that time from Collingwood, and firmly cut past point
it's a shot a ball, but that time they miss out as Taylor swishes outside off
squared up a fraction, but it's another run as the ball bobbles into space
clipped through midwicket, but only one run as it's Flintoff lurking on the boundary's edge
airy clip through midwicket, perhaps a touch beaten in flight there?
rapped on the pad as he aims to work through the leg-side again
another easy single as that's driven down to long-off. New Zealand are coasting at the moment
tip-and-run stuff. Another single straight down the ground
Fleming misses another attempted sweep. Rare respite for the scoreboard operator
shorter and carved through the covers off the back foot. The sweeper is on hand to protect the boundary

England have got the wicket! And it's a run-out from Flintoff's first ball of the new spell! Fleming defended into the covers and set off for the run, Taylor hesitated, Fleming stopped dead, retreated, Taylor kept on coming, and Flintoff fielded the ball and hurtled down to the non-striker's end! Big breakthrough
outside off stump, whistles through to the keeper
excellent line and length, heavy delivery through to the keeper
more of the same. Flintoff is head and shoulders above every other seamer in this attack
watchful from Fleming. He knows the scoring opportunities will come again when the lesser bowlers return
a fifth leave-alone in a row from Fleming, and that's a wicket maiden for Flintoff and England
good start. Wicket-to-wicket stuff, turned into the leg-side - slightly airborne
hint of width, driven square to point
pushed into the covers. More dot-balls to tighten the sinews
relief for Fleming as he pushes this down the ground
nudged into the leg-side
forward once again and turned wide of short midwicket for another single. Tidy over though, and now it's back to Flintoff
short and a bit of width, but too quick for Styris to capitalise. Point tidies up
fuller, straighter, sharper. Defended off the back foot
90.4mph (144kph), and nipping back into the pads. An appeal for Flintoff, but they cross for a welcome single
short and shovelled into the leg-side. Lucky to get away with that as it looped into no-man's land at short midwicket. Flintoff is rattling the Kiwis, but how long can England persevere with him?
an absolute beauty! Pitched on off, held its line and zipped past the edge! Wonderful bowling
shorter but easily worked off the pads behind square for a single. Great over, and the pressure continues to mount on both sides
driven down the ground to long-on
outside off, and Fleming plays on the up through point for another bout of strike-rotation
more singles, but those are preferable to boundaries as far as England are concerned. Worked through midwicket this time
a bit of a clout, but more runs through midwicket
full and straight, and worked into the leg-side. New Zealand content to milk the bowling for now
nicely timed down the ground, but long-off fields without any alarms. Six singles in the over
good start from Plunkett, short but straight and takes the shoulder of the bat through gully
that was a big wind-up from Styris - the intention is clear, he wants to hit Plunkett off his line and length
tight so far though. Fleming is cramped for room by this one as he defends off the back foot
that's the shot! Plunkett dropped a fraction short and Fleming was onto it in a flash. The line was okay, but no-one sweeping at deep midwicket
nudged into the leg-side again, and a quick single. Good batting
good finish from Plunkett. Outside off, on a good length, defended into the leg-side.
drilled into the deep, and two more. 98 for Fleming
there's that quick single that caused confusion with Taylor. But Fleming's on 99
big stride, full swing, fielded at long-on
short ball, good thinking. That was 80mph (129kph) and straight. Fended to gully
drawn forward again but mistimes his drive. A touch of nerves?
fantastic fielding from Dalrymple at point! Fleming thought that was through the gap, but Dalrymple pounced like a pouncy thing to cut off the hundredth run
premeditated chip over his shoulder, and excellent fielding by Ian Bell on the boundary cuts off two
quicker delivery zips past Styris's bat and well taken by Nixon
firm drive through the covers. Long chase round the boundary's edge but one run saved
bowling Monty ... looped it up to tempt the big shot, but fields in his followthrough
there it is! Fleming's got his hundred with a clip through midwicket. He completes it with a dive but he was safely home. That's his seventh ODI hundred, and what a moment to produce it
pushed down the ground again, and that's the 200 up as well
turned into the leg-side again, another single ticked off
cunning improvisation from Styris - another premeditated sweep and that's lobbed down to the boundary's edge for two more

He's holed out to Monty! Slightly shorter from Collingwood, but it was a slower ball, and Panesar at mid-off held on to a simple chance that no doubt looked pretty difficult as it looped towards him! Could there be a late twist in this match?
back on a conventional length, and driven into the covers
tight line and length. Vaughan fields in that very straight silly mid-off position that England have been known to use against such biffers as Matthew Hayden
Oram is off the mark with a steer down to third man. It's shaping up to be a tight finish
speared across the left hander who leaves it alone
pushed out to gully
wide, a big mow and a thick edges goes right down what would have been first slip's gullet ... Nixon watches, Flintoff at third slip watches, and the ball rockets to the third-man boundary
slightly fuller, again Oram looks to crash it out the ground ... this time the edge is finer and at a perfect height for Nixon who only has to move a foot or two to his left
a peach, cuts McCullum in half and Nixon takes it with accompanying chirps and chirrups
pushed to the right of mid-on
McCullum pushes firmly forward into the covers
McCullum back and punches it into the covers where Vaughan falls over and misses the ball
Fleming waits and looks to place the ball into the off side but, like a homing missile, it goes straight to gully
hit back at Collingwood who half stops, but that's enough to prevent the run
clipped into the leg side and Panesar fields but cannot stop the single
full and McCullum can't get any power on the drive and mid-off races in to pick up
Fleming moves to leg, swipes, and misses
shapes to flick to leg, it bobbles off his thigh pad and Nixon runs round to field
straight and full, McCullum shimmies to leg and is bowled off his pads
he's greeted by a bouncer which Vettori bends double to avoid ... and after a long delay it's given as a wide. Vaughan is absolutely livid, Plunkett shakes his head in bemusement
prodded into the off side
Vettori smashes Plunkett straight down the ground for four
same stroke but not hit nearly as hard and mid-on rushes round to cut the ball off
Vettori moves to leg early and slogs - no other word - that inches wide of midwicket and to the boundary
same line but fuller, almost yorker length, and Vettori hits to Vaughan at midwicket
right up in the blockhole, squeezed out into the off for a single
driven hard back to Collingwood who drops down quickly to stop the ball
full toss - just - and wristily turned round the corner but he finds the one man in the whole area
full toss heaved right to Vaughan at midwicket. Collingwood finishes with 2 for 46 to add to his hundred and New Zealand need something Lazarus-like now
full and cracked into the covers for one. England will be happy with that as it gets Fleming off strike and uses another ball
short and steered to third man, lovely placement and Panesar chugging round from third man can't get it
peach! pitched up and beats Franklin neck and crop, and misses his off stump by about an inch
pushed to short extra cover, Vaughan picks up and hurls the ball at Flintoff from about ten yards, Flintoff is upended and they run two overthrows. Vaughan sheepishly holds his hands up ... mea culpa
tried to give himself room to hit through the covers, a thick and edge and Nixon holds the catch. That could be that ...
Bond steps a yard outside leg and squirts it to point. Again, the fielder leathers it at the stumps when there was nothing to be gained other than overthrows
short of a length, Bond aims a rather odd flip-drive and misses by a mile
slower ball heaved into the leg side
Bond moves to leg, Mahmood follows, and the ball ends up via an edge at long leg
driven in th air down the ground, not timed and Flintoff ambles in to field
slower ball, as badly disguised a pantomime dame, and it's launched over wide mid-on
slashed off the outside edge to third man
wide and right up on the crease, Franklin can't do anything with it. A few boos as the more partisan spectators think it should have been a called
slashed to third man, Plunkett's return is a yard over Nixon's head and much head shaking as there are more overthrows
run to backward point
Bond hot-foots it towards cover and his attempted flick to leg misses ... his off stump!
this time Bond moves top leg and swats it to the man in the deep on the cover boundary
and swing, an edge and the ball races to the third-man rope. Flintoff grins ...he clearly thinks it's academic
Bond moves a yard to leg, Mahmood follows him ("No, it was just a rubbish ball," claims Miller) and they run a bye as Nixon makes a tumbling stop
straight ball, a big swing edged into his body and another one
clubbed through the covers for another two
again Bond heads towards square leg and his attempted drive is missed and the ball passes between bat and leg stump
full toss, swatted into space
beaten outside off stump, a loud appeal from Mahmood and Nixon but it's immaterial, the game is over and England will meet Australia in the best-of-three final
